      <p class="eyebrow">Guide · The far north</p>
      <h1>Praying by a sun that won&rsquo;t set</h1>
      <p class="lede">How Isfar finds prayer times where the night disappears — and why a seventh of the night, honestly divided, is all it takes.</p>
      <div class="byline">
        <span>9 June 2026 · updated 10 June</span>
        <span>12 min read</span>
        <span>The engineering behind <a href="/">Isfar</a></span>
      </div>

      <h2 id="a-flight-with-a-hole-in-it">A flight with a hole in it</h2>
      <p>This feature began with a bug report that wasn&rsquo;t a bug. A traveller looked up <strong>BA48, Seattle to London</strong> — an overnight hop over the Canadian Arctic and the North Atlantic in June — and the app showed Maghrib, and then&hellip; Dhuhr. No Isha. No Fajr. Two prayers had simply fallen out of the sky.</p>
      <p>The app wasn&rsquo;t broken. The night was gone. For months either side of midsummer, along the top of that route — it crests above the Arctic Circle near the Davis Strait — the sun never gets far enough below the horizon for Isha or Fajr to <em>exist</em> — at least not by the rules most prayer apps use. The calculation didn&rsquo;t fail loudly; it returned nothing, and the nothing looked like an answer.</p>
      <p>Fixing that properly took us through some beautiful astronomy, several scholarly opinions, and a string of edge cases that each broke a different way. This post walks the same road, slowly. By the end you&rsquo;ll know exactly what Isfar does on a far-north flight, and why.</p>
      <p>One thing this post is <strong>not</strong>: a fiqh ruling. The juristic groundwork here was laid by scholars, and the disagreements between them are theirs to hold. Our job was narrower — take the recognized opinions and make them <em>work inside an app</em> for an ordinary traveller. Where we had to choose, we chose for clarity and marked the result as an estimate. Follow your own scholars and community where you land.</p>

      <h2 id="five-prayers">Five prayers, five positions of the sun</h2>
      <p>Prayer times aren&rsquo;t arbitrary clock times. Each one is pinned to something the sun does:</p>
      <div class="tablewrap">
        <table>
          <caption class="vh">The five daily prayers and the solar moment that defines each one.</caption>
          <thead><tr><th>Prayer</th><th>The sun&rsquo;s moment</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Fajr</th><td>First light of dawn — the sky begins to glow while the sun is still well below the horizon</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Dhuhr</th><td>Just past solar noon — the sun crests your meridian and begins to lean west</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Asr</th><td>Mid-afternoon — when a shadow reaches a set proportion of its object</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Maghrib</th><td>Sunset — the sun&rsquo;s disk slips below the horizon</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Isha</th><td>Nightfall — the last twilight fades and the sky is truly dark</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>Three of these are sturdy. Solar noon happens every day, everywhere. Sunset and the shadow-lengths of afternoon exist anywhere the sun rises at all. But Fajr and Isha are different — they don&rsquo;t mark the sun&rsquo;s <em>disk</em>, they mark its <em>light</em>.</p>

      <h2 id="dawn-and-dusk-are-angles">Dawn and dusk are angles</h2>
      <p>How do you put a number on &ldquo;first light&rdquo; or &ldquo;true dark&rdquo;? Astronomers — and the Muslim world&rsquo;s calculation authorities — answer with an <strong>angle</strong>: how far the sun sits <em>below</em> the horizon. At sunset the sun is at 0°. As it keeps sinking, twilight fades. Somewhere between <strong>12° and 18° below the horizon</strong>, the glow dies and the stars take the sky.</p>

      <AnimTwilightAngle />

      <p>The world&rsquo;s calculation authorities each fixed their own number from long observation: the Muslim World League uses <strong>18°</strong> for Fajr, ISNA (North America) <strong>15°</strong>, Egypt&rsquo;s authority <strong>19.5°</strong> — a shade deeper still, fixed from observations in clear desert air. A dozen conventions, each defensible. This is why two apps can disagree by half an hour — they&rsquo;re loyal to different authorities, not different math. <a href="/">Isfar lets you pick yours</a> in Settings and computes it faithfully.</p>
      <p>At most latitudes, that&rsquo;s the whole story. In Istanbul or New York, the sun dives deep below the horizon every single night of the year, sails past 15°, past 18°, and the angles always have a moment to mark. The method you choose just works.</p>
      <p>Then you fly north.</p>

      <h2 id="what-latitude-does">What latitude does to the night</h2>
      <p>The Earth is tilted about 23.4°. In northern summer, the top of the planet leans <em>toward</em> the sun — so the further north you stand, the shallower the sun&rsquo;s dip below your horizon at midnight. It sets, but it doesn&rsquo;t go <em>down</em> very far. It grazes along just under the horizon, and the twilight never quite dies.</p>

      <AnimTiltedEarth />

      <p>Watch what happens to a June night as you move north.</p>
      <p><strong>London (51.5°N), June 21, with a 15° method.</strong> It still works — barely. True dark arrives at <strong>00:49</strong> and first light returns at <strong>01:16</strong>. Isha and Fajr both exist, separated by a window of twenty-seven minutes.</p>
      <p><strong>London, same night, with an 18° method.</strong> The sun never reaches 18° below the horizon at all. Ask the math anyway and Fajr and Isha both land on <strong>01:02 — the same minute</strong>. The angle a traveller chose in good faith has, for a few weeks of the year, stopped describing anything real.</p>
      <p><strong>Stockholm (59.3°N), June 21.</strong> Now even 15° is unreachable. The night between sunset (22:08 local) and sunrise (03:31) never gets properly dark at all. There is simply no instant of &ldquo;true dark&rdquo; to point to.</p>
      <p>And it keeps going. Cross the Arctic Circle (66.5°N — the line Rovaniemi in Finnish Lapland sits on) and in midsummer the sun stops <em>setting</em> altogether — the midnight sun. In Tromsø, Norway, it stays above the horizon from mid-May to late July. No sunset means no Maghrib moment, no night, no dawn. Three of the five prayers have lost their sun-marks; only the noon and afternoon prayers still have a sky to point at.</p>

      <AnimShrinkingDip />

      <h2 id="the-scholarly-toolkit">The scholarly toolkit — and where each tool breaks</h2>
      <p>None of this is new. Scholars have written about prayer at extreme latitudes for centuries, and several practical conventions are in wide use. And none of it changes what is owed: the scholars&rsquo; shared starting point is that the prayers themselves remain. When the sky withholds its usual signs, they reach for the Prophet&rsquo;s ﷺ answer about a day that would stretch like a year — <em>estimate its measure</em>. The conventions below are ways of doing that estimation (<em>taqdīr</em>) with care.</p>
      <p>We tried each of them in software, and each one breaks somewhere specific. (Details of the juristic reasoning belong to the scholars; what follows is engineering.)</p>
      <p><strong>Use the chosen angle, always.</strong> Breaks first. As London-in-June showed, an 18° angle stops existing at ~48°N (Vienna) in midsummer, 15° at ~52°N (Birmingham). You cannot compute a time from an angle the sun never reaches.</p>
      <p><strong>Middle of the night.</strong> When the angle fails, treat the night&rsquo;s midpoint as a boundary — Isha must arrive by it, Fajr won&rsquo;t begin before it. Simple — but at exactly the latitudes that need the rule, both times get pinned to that same instant. Stockholm, June 21: Fajr <strong>00:50</strong>, Isha <strong>00:50</strong> — the same minute, in the small hours. This is the silent default in much prayer software, and it&rsquo;s why far-north timetables so often collapse into a single strange minute.</p>
      <p><strong>A seventh of the night</strong> (<em>sub&lsquo; al-layl</em> — the convention moonsighting.com favors for these latitudes). Divide the actual night, sunset to sunrise, into sevenths: Isha falls after the first seventh, Fajr begins at the last. At Stockholm in June this produces a humane, prayable schedule: Maghrib 22:08, <strong>Isha 22:54</strong>, <strong>Fajr 02:45</strong>, sunrise 03:31. It uses <em>your own</em> sky, scales with the seasons, and degrades gracefully&hellip; as long as there <em>is</em> a night to divide.</p>
      <p>That last clause is the catch. Cross the Arctic Circle in summer and the night is gone — a seventh of nothing is nothing. (Just <em>below</em> the circle the night merely thins: at Akureyri in northern Iceland the June night lasts thirty-seven minutes. And thin, it turns out, is not the same as gone. We&rsquo;ll put that to the test below.)</p>
      <p><strong>The nearest place with a valid time</strong> (<em>aqrab al-bilād</em>). When your own sky fails, borrow from the closest latitude where the calculation still works. Sound idea — but implemented literally, software slides to the <em>mathematical boundary</em>: the exact latitude where the night is fifteen minutes long. The borrowed times sit right at the breaking point and lurch from day to day as that boundary moves.</p>

      <AnimCollapsingNight />

      <p class="pull">Every tool is good. Every tool has a cliff. The design question was never &ldquo;which opinion is correct&rdquo; — it was <em>where to stand</em> so the cliffs don&rsquo;t reach the user.</p>

      <h2 id="two-seasons">Summer breaks the night. Winter breaks the day.</h2>
      <p>Here&rsquo;s the part that surprised us during testing: <strong>this is a two-season problem, and the seasons break different prayers.</strong></p>
      <p>Summer is the night-killer. Below the Arctic Circle, the <em>days</em> are long but normal — the sun rises and sets — so Dhuhr, Asr and Maghrib are all real. It&rsquo;s the twilight prayers, Fajr and Isha, that fail first, starting around 48–55°N — Vienna to Kazan — depending on your angle. Cross the circle and Maghrib finally goes too.</p>
      <p>Winter is the opposite — and gentler, for longer. A short, dark December day at Stockholm or Helsinki is <em>perfect</em> for prayer times: the sun rises, sets, and plunges deep below the horizon. Every angle works. <strong>At 55–60°N, winter is the easy season.</strong> The methods that strained all summer relax completely.</p>
      <p>But cross the Arctic Circle in winter and the failure inverts. Now the sun never <em>rises</em> — polar night. Maghrib has no sunset to mark it, and with no sunrise either there is no night — sunset to sunrise — for Fajr and Isha to belong to. (Twilight itself survives: Tromsø&rsquo;s polar noon glows blue for hours. But the day it should border is gone.) <strong>Asr breaks too</strong>, for a reason we found oddly poignant: Asr is defined by the length of a shadow, and a sun that never rises casts none. Even Dhuhr — solar &ldquo;noon&rdquo; — happens with the sun below the horizon; the moment exists, but the sun beneath it never rises.</p>
      <p>So the full picture, for Tromsø across one year, prayer by prayer:</p>
      <div class="tablewrap">
        <table>
          <caption class="vh">Tromsø across one year: which prayers are real and which are estimated, by season.</caption>
          <thead><tr><th>Season</th><th>Fajr</th><th>Dhuhr</th><th>Asr</th><th>Maghrib</th><th>Isha</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>March / October</th><td class="t-real">real</td><td class="t-real">real</td><td class="t-real">real</td><td class="t-real">real</td><td class="t-real">real</td></tr>
            <tr><th>June (midnight sun)</th><td class="t-est">estimated</td><td class="t-real">real</td><td class="t-real">real</td><td class="t-est">estimated</td><td class="t-est">estimated</td></tr>
            <tr><th>December (polar night)</th><td class="t-est">estimated</td><td class="t-est">estimated*</td><td class="t-est">estimated</td><td class="t-est">estimated</td><td class="t-est">estimated</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="note">*Dhuhr&rsquo;s solar-noon instant is always defined — in polar night we keep its exact time but flag it, because calling it &ldquo;midday&rdquo; when the sun never rose would overstate what we know.</p>
      <p>Note the first row. For four to five months of the year, depending on your angle — late winter into spring, and again through autumn — even Tromsø, 350&nbsp;km past the Arctic Circle, has perfectly ordinary prayer times, and Isfar computes them with your chosen method, no fallbacks, no estimates. The machinery below only wakes when the sky stops offering its usual signs.</p>

      <AnimYearWheel />

      <h2 id="what-isfar-does-at-high-latitudes">What Isfar actually does at high latitudes</h2>
      <p>All of the above condenses to three rules, applied automatically, <strong>per prayer, per date, per position along your flight path</strong>:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Wherever the sun reaches your method&rsquo;s angle — use it.</strong> Your chosen authority&rsquo;s real times, untouched. This covers almost every flight, and even the far north for most of the year.</li>
        <li><strong>Where the angle is out of reach but the sun still rises and sets — divide your own night by sevenths.</strong> Your local night, sunset to sunrise, portioned following the old juristic convention moonsighting.com recommends — at <em>any</em> latitude. A seventh is less than half, so however short the night runs, Isha lands after the sunset you can see, Fajr begins before the coming sunrise, and the two never meet in the middle. The result is marked as an estimate.</li>
        <li><strong>And on the few days a place has no night at all — midnight sun, polar night — borrow the night from latitude 60°N</strong>, at your own longitude. Sixty is about the furthest north that keeps a dependable night all year, and the line where the region&rsquo;s great cities actually live — Stockholm, Oslo, Helsinki, St Petersburg — so the borrowed times are lived times, not a mathematical edge. The whole night comes along (Maghrib, Isha, Fajr, sunrise), there is no local sunset or sunrise left to disagree with it, and a banner says why (&ldquo;the sun won&rsquo;t set at Tromsø tonight&hellip;&rdquo;).</li>
      </ol>

      <AnimSixtyFloor />
      <p>The switch between rule 1 and rule 2 isn&rsquo;t a line of latitude — it&rsquo;s <em>your angle meeting your sky</em>. Choose an 18° method and the fallback engages further south than your neighbour&rsquo;s 15°; in winter it disengages entirely. The app adapts to the opinion you follow rather than overriding it.</p>
      <p>And everything estimated <em>says so</em>. A <code>~</code> before the time, an &ldquo;estimate&rdquo; tag on the card, and a plain-language note. We&rsquo;d rather show you an honest approximation than a confident fiction — the same instinct that makes the app nudge Maghrib a few minutes later at cruising altitude (when we must err, we err toward the sun you can actually see) and compute every prayer from the sky outside your window, not the one at your destination.</p>
      <p>A worked example, the day we kept testing: <strong>Oslo → Tromsø, December 21st</strong>, landing in polar night. Before departure, Oslo&rsquo;s real Asr (13:04) and Maghrib (15:08). Isha arrives mid-flight at 17:19 — a real time, not an estimate, because the night below the aircraft at 62°N (level with Ålesund, over inland Norway) is still deep enough for the angle. After landing: Fajr ~06:26, borrowed from latitude 60° — where a 15° dawn still exists even in late December — and Dhuhr ~11:44, Tromsø&rsquo;s own solar noon, flagged because the sun beneath it never rises. Both carry the <code>~</code>, under a banner that says the sun will not rise tomorrow in Tromsø, and that&rsquo;s why.</p>
      <p>And BA48, the flight that opened this story? It shows all five prayers now. Isha and Fajr are back, each carrying a quiet <code>~</code>, both portioned from the thin night the route itself crosses. Present, labelled, no longer a hole in the sky.</p>

      <h2 id="does-a-seventh-actually-work">Does a seventh of the night actually work?</h2>
      <p>Here is the worry, stated plainly. Near the Arctic Circle the night thins to minutes — and a seventh of a twenty-minute night would put Isha three minutes after Maghrib and give Fajr a three-minute window. True times, barely usable ones. If that happened on real routes, the rule would be elegant on paper and useless in the air.</p>
      <p>So we flew it — the June solstice timetable, the season at its worst. (An earlier version of this page defended a heavier fallback, borrowing the 60° night everywhere above the 60th parallel, until these same flights showed it calling Maghrib in daylight and announcing Fajr after the cabin had watched the sun rise. The simpler rule won.) What the engine shows today, every row pinned by a test:</p>
      <div class="tablewrap">
        <table>
          <caption class="vh">Isfar&rsquo;s June-solstice output across the real far-north timetable.</caption>
          <thead><tr><th>Flight</th><th>The June sky</th><th>What Isfar shows</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>BA48 · Seattle→London</th><td>crests 67.5°N; the cabin watches the sun rise at 07:55</td><td>~Fajr 07:49 — six minutes <em>before</em> that sunrise</td></tr>
            <tr><th>AC854 · Vancouver→London</th><td>crests 68.3°N; cabin sunrise 08:36</td><td>~Fajr 08:29 — seven minutes before</td></tr>
            <tr><th>AY16 · New York→Helsinki</th><td>crests 64.4°N</td><td>~Fajr 06:21, sun still 2.5° down</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SK910 · Newark→Oslo</th><td>crests 62.1°N</td><td>~Fajr 06:01, sun 3.6° down</td></tr>
            <tr><th>BA268 · Los Angeles→London</th><td>crests only 62.3°N</td><td>Fajr 08:23 — real, no estimate needed</td></tr>
            <tr><th>FI455 · London→Keflavík</th><td>lands 23:35, at 64°N</td><td>~Fajr 02:42 — 28 minutes before sunrise</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Reykjavík→Akureyri</th><td>a 37-minute night at 65.7°N</td><td>Maghrib 00:56 · ~Isha 01:01 · ~Fajr 01:27, with a banner</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Stockholm→Luleå</th><td>a 60-minute night at 65.5°N</td><td>~Isha nine minutes after Maghrib, with the banner</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="note">Times in the destination&rsquo;s clock, on the June solstice timetable, with a 15° (ISNA) method; <code>~</code> marks an estimate.</p>
      <p>The compressed night everyone fears turns out to be hard to even find. The strip where a June night dips under half an hour is about five kilometres wide — an aircraft crosses it in twenty seconds — and the North Atlantic tracks where flights actually spend their hours, between 58° and 63°N, keep nights of three to six hours and prayer gaps of half an hour or more. On the ground it reaches a handful of small airports, and the worst of them is Akureyri: thirty-seven minutes of night, in the weeks around the solstice. There Isfar prints the times as they are, says so in a banner — <em>the night here is 37 minutes long</em> — and leans on the oldest of the traveller&rsquo;s concessions: Maghrib and Isha, prayed together.</p>
      <p>A short night honestly divided turns out to be a better companion than a long night borrowed from a sky the traveller isn&rsquo;t under. That is the whole rule.</p>

      <h2 id="questions-travellers-ask">Questions travellers ask</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <h3>What time is Isha when the sun never sets?</h3>
        <p>When there is no true nightfall to mark it, Isfar estimates Isha by portioning the night into sevenths — your own night where one still exists, the night at latitude 60°N where it doesn&rsquo;t. The time carries a <code>~</code> because it is an estimate, not an observation.</p>
        <h3>Do Fajr and Isha still apply during the midnight sun?</h3>
        <p>The prayers remain; only their sun-marks are missing. Scholars offer several conventions for estimating the times, and Isfar applies them automatically, labelling every estimate. Follow your own scholars and community for what the estimate means in practice.</p>
        <h3>Why latitude 60°N and not the nearest valid latitude?</h3>
        <p>The nearest valid latitude is a moving mathematical edge where the night is a fifteen-minute sliver. 60°N is about the furthest north with a dependable night all year — and the line where Stockholm, Oslo, St Petersburg and Helsinki actually live.</p>
        <h3>Are far-north prayer times always estimates?</h3>
        <p>No. For four to five months of the year — late winter into spring, and again through autumn — the sun even at Tromsø rises, sets and dips deep enough for the usual angles, and your method&rsquo;s real times apply untouched. The estimates wake through the bright months around the midnight sun, and again in the darkest weeks of polar night.</p>
        <h3>What if the night is only half an hour long?</h3>
        <p>Then the times say so. At Akureyri in northern Iceland the June night lasts 37 minutes: Isha lands five minutes after Maghrib, and Fajr keeps a six-minute window before sunrise. A short night is still a real night — Isfar shows it as it is and notes its length plainly, and the traveller&rsquo;s old concession of combining Maghrib with Isha was made for exactly this.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="standing-on-others-work">Standing on others&rsquo; work</h2>
      <p>The shape of this solution — <em>use the real angle while it exists, portion the night where it doesn&rsquo;t, and slide to a humane reference latitude rather than a mathematical edge</em> — follows the framework laid out by Khalid Shaukat at <a href="https://moonsighting.com/how-we.html" rel="noopener">moonsighting.com</a>, whose latitude-and-season treatment of true dawn (<em>ṣubḥ ṣādiq</em>) and twilight (<em>shafaq</em>) has quietly anchored sensible high-latitude timetables for years. The celestial mechanics are <a href="https://github.com/batoulapps/adhan-js" rel="noopener">adhan-js</a>, the open-source library trusted across the Muslim app ecosystem; Isfar chooses <em>which question to ask it</em>, and never computes a prayer time by hand.</p>
      <p>And the deeper debt is to the scholars — classical and contemporary — who took &ldquo;what do we do when the sun won&rsquo;t set?&rdquo; seriously enough to leave the rest of us several good answers. We didn&rsquo;t adjudicate between them, and won&rsquo;t. We built a traveller&rsquo;s instrument that uses their work honestly, labels its approximations, and gets out of the way.</p>
      <p>Safe travels. <em>Safar mubārak</em> — <span class="ar" dir="rtl">سفر مبارك</span></p>

